Kerri Anderson¶

Load Modeling AI/ML GreatLearning Project 3 July 2021

This project is focused on helping a bank grow its loan (asset) business. We will use information from last year's campaign to identify which customers are likely to puchase a personal loan and will work to target them with marketing strategies. Following initial data exploration, a logistic regression model and decision tree will be built and compared on the test dataset for performance.

Please note, some of the coding for this program is taken from class material such as the lecture, case studies, or mentored learning sessions. No other sources were used for code blocks.

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

Initial data exploration conclusions¶

Upon initial exploration, the values for the data seem reasonable without the need for much data cleansing.

It would be beneficial to explore the bivariate distributions of the data.

It would be beneficial to create a debt:income ratio to evaluate the correlation with the outcome variable.

It would be beneficial to create a combined indicator for the CD and securities accounts to see if it is associated more strongly with the target outcome.

# function to plot stacked bar chart


def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True).sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 5, 6))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left", frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()

def plot_corr(df, size=30):
    corr = df.corr()
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(size, size))
    ax.matshow(corr)
    plt.xticks(range(len(corr.columns)), corr.columns)
    plt.yticks(range(len(corr.columns)), corr.columns)
    for (i, j), z in np.ndenumerate(corr):
        ax.text(j, i, '{:0.1f}'.format(z), ha='center', va='center')

I am going to create three datasets to train/test the data. The first includes the original variables (excluding ID and zip code), the second includes variables which I created in addition to the original ones, the third has a reduced number of variables, based on observations in the bivariate analysis (remove one of pair of highly correlated variables such as age and experience).

Each of these sets of variables can be used to compare model performance and the best model can be chosen. We want to find the simplest model that provides the most predictive value.

The goal is to properly identify individuals that will purchase a loan. The bank wants to set up a marketing approach to target individuals to buy a loan. It is alright to have more false positives, to a certain degree, but we want to reduce false negatives. It is a small price to market to too many people, but there is opportunity lost cost if we miss someone with our marketing that could have purchased a personal loan. Want to ensure a strong recall with reasonable precision (balance between lost opportunity cost, and wasted marketing dollars on those who will not purchase a loan even with good marketing)

# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using sklearn

def model_performance_classification_sklearn_with_threshold(model, predictors, target, threshold=0.5):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics, based on the threshold specified, to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    threshold: threshold for classifying the observation as class 1
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred_prob = model.predict_proba(predictors)[:, 1]
    pred_thres = pred_prob > threshold
    pred = np.round(pred_thres)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "Accuracy": acc,
            "Recall": recall,
            "Precision": precision,
            "F1": f1,
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf
In [80]:
# defining a function to plot the confusion_matrix of a classification model built using sklearn
def confusion_matrix_sklearn_with_threshold(model, predictors, target, threshold=0.5):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix, based on the threshold specified, with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    threshold: threshold for classifying the observation as class 1
    """
    pred_prob = model.predict_proba(predictors)[:, 1]
    pred_thres = pred_prob > threshold
    y_pred = np.round(pred_thres)

    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

The model performance was best (highest recall in test dataset) with the additional variables, however, the value was very close to that of the original model. Given this additional complexity, with little gain in model performance, the original variables should remain as our chosen predictors. We will move forward with the original set of variables to build and evaluate a decision tree model.

Higher debt:income ratio indicates more likely to take out a personal loan, and did provide some additional information to the model, but this number also represents that a personal taking out the loan is more likely to default if they aren't able to pay back. We won't include this in the marketing model. The purpose of this model is to market effectively so that people purchase a personal loan. The debt to income ratio should be considered in the underwiting model to determine if the bank will take on the risk. Debt to income should not be considered in this marketing model.

In the original model we see that those with more education, larger family size, and a CD account are more likely to take out a personal loan. We should definitely target this group of customers. We also see that using online services reduces taking out a loan so we might want to target those that come into our banking locations by having printed material in the banks that target these customers. For online customers, we might need to find a unique approach. Customers with CD accounts should be easy to recognize in our system. Education and family size may be in our system (because we have data) or we may need to purchase this data from a third party or vendor. This cost should be considered in the investment cost of the marketing strategy.

## Function to create confusion matrix
def make_confusion_matrix(model,y_actual,labels=[1, 0]):
    '''
    model : classifier to predict values of X
    y_actual : ground truth  
    
    '''
    y_predict = model.predict(x_test_orig)
    cm=metrics.confusion_matrix( y_actual, y_predict, labels=[0, 1])
    df_cm = pd.DataFrame(cm, index = [i for i in ["Actual - No","Actual - Yes"]],
                  columns = [i for i in ['Predicted - No','Predicted - Yes']])
    group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}".format(value) for value in
                cm.flatten()]
    group_percentages = ["{0:.2%}".format(value) for value in
                         cm.flatten()/np.sum(cm)]
    labels = [f"{v1}\n{v2}" for v1, v2 in
              zip(group_counts,group_percentages)]
    labels = np.asarray(labels).reshape(2,2)
    plt.figure(figsize = (10,7))
    sns.heatmap(df_cm, annot=labels,fmt='')
    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')

##  Function to calculate recall score
def get_recall_score(model):
    '''
    model : classifier to predict values of X

    '''
    pred_train = model.predict(x_train_orig)
    pred_test = model.predict(x_test_orig)
    print("Recall on training set : ",metrics.recall_score(y_train_orig,pred_train))
    print("Recall on test set : ",metrics.recall_score(y_test_orig,pred_test))

optimize decision tree with hyperparameter tuning¶

In [123]:
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
In [124]:
# Choose the type of classifier. 
estimator = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=1)

# Grid of parameters to choose from
## add from article
parameters = {'max_depth': np.arange(1,10), 
              'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 5, 7, 10,15,20],
              'max_leaf_nodes' : [2, 3, 5, 10],
              'min_impurity_decrease': [0.001,0.01,0.1]
             }

# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations
acc_scorer = metrics.make_scorer(metrics.recall_score)

# Run the grid search
grid_obj = GridSearchCV(estimator, parameters, scoring=acc_scorer,cv=5)
grid_obj = grid_obj.fit(x_train_orig, y_train_orig)

# Set the clf to the best combination of parameters
estimator = grid_obj.best_estimator_

# Fit the best algorithm to the data. 
estimator.fit(x_train_orig, y_train_orig)

Key variables to target individuals who are likely to take out a personal loan include higher level of education, increased income, increased family size, CC average monthly charges, and having a CD loan. The bank should develop special marketing material for these invididuals and can further classify how to target them based on if they use online accounts or not (can be used to market online or send direct mailers based on their preference for interacting with the bank).

The bank will then be able to measure the success of this marketing campaign to develop future marketing campaigns.
